[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Older issues of software magazines such as IEEE Software and Communications of the ACM from the 1970s and 1980s focused on foundational topics like testing philosophy, specific testing techniques, and maintenance challenges.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Myers (1979) is the classic text, describing the philosophy of testing as well as several specific techniques.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The  May  1994  issue  of Communications  of  the  ACM is  a  special  issue  on reverse engineering.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The  January 1990 issue had maintenance, reverse engineering, and design recovery as its theme.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These older issues also addressed testing considerations such as black-box testing and inspection techniques, and maintenance issues including legacy systems and reverse engineering.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Beizer (1990) offers a good overview of testing considerations and techniques, with many references to key papers in the field. His 1995 book focuses particularly on black-box testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are many good papers describing the use of inspections, including Weller (1993 and 1994) and Grady and van Slack (1994). Gilb and Graham's book (1993) on inspections is a good, comprehensive, and practical guide.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The  January 1995 issue focused on legacy systems, and the January 1993 issue has a good article by Wilde, Matthews, and Huitt on the special maintenance problems of object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "More recent issues of software magazines have expanded focus to include test-driven development, software dependability, usability testing, and the challenges of testing object-oriented systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The May 2007 issue addressed test-driven development.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software dependability and safety-critical systems are receiving more and more attention, and there are many good articles and books about the key issues, including Leveson (1996, 1997).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Usability tests and more general usability issues are covered in depth in Hix and Hartson (1993).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The September 1994 issue of Communications of the ACM discusses special considerations in testing object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Recent issues also address broader software engineering topics such as software certification, licensing, ethics, and group decision-making models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The January/February 2000 issue of IEEE Software addresses the more general question of what we can learn from other disciplines.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Discussion of software engineering licensing is addressed in the November/ December 1999 issue of IEEE Software and the May 2000 issue of IEEE Computer.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An excellent discussion of ethics and the role of personal responsibility can be found in Baase (2002).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The social science literature is rich with information about group decisionmaking. Klein (1998) is a very readable introduction to the recognition-primed decision model.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Robertsons' requirements definition template, available at the Atlantic Systems Guild website (http://www.systemsguild.com), is a comprehensive tool designed to support the elicitation and validation of software requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com.This template is accompanied by a description of the Volere process model, which is a complete process for eliciting and checking a set of requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template is particularly helpful during the requirements elicitation and validation phases of the software development process, as it provides a structured approach to capturing and checking requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This template is accompanied by a description of the Volere process model, which is a complete process for eliciting and checking a set of requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To use the template effectively for validating requirements, developers need to engage in activities such as eliciting requirements from stakeholders, documenting them clearly using the template, and systematically checking the requirements for completeness, consistency, and correctness.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Volere requirements process model (Robertson and Robertson 1999), as shown in Figure 4.2, suggests some additional sources for requirements, such as templates and libraries of requirements from related systems that we have developed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers applying the template must possess strong interpersonal skills to manage different stakeholder viewpoints and technical skills to understand the feasibility and implications of requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the many skills of a requirements analyst is the ability to understand each view and capture the requirements in a way that reflects the concerns of each participant.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "good requirements analysis requires excellent interpersonal skills as well as solid technical skills.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template helps uncover errors and faults such as incomplete requirements, conflicting stakeholder views, and overlooked critical functions, by providing a structured and comprehensive framework for requirements capture and validation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In addition to interviewing stakeholders, other means of eliciting requirements include the old system continues to be used because it provides some critical function that the designers of the new system overlooked The Volere requirements process model (Robertson and Robertson 1999), as shown in Figure 4.2, suggests some additional sources for requirements, such as templates and libraries of requirements from related systems that we have developed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge on methods for studying maintenance activities involves observing the work practices of software engineers engaged in maintenance projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Researchers with the Institute for Information Technology of the National Research Council, Canada, study maintenance by observing the work practices of software engineers who are engaged in maintenance projects. A paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge summarizes the methods they use to collect this type of data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the viewpoint of a software maintainer, the data collection methods are likely to be somewhat disruptive because maintenance work often involves balancing management priorities, user demands, and technical needs, and maintainers must handle complex, sometimes poorly documented systems under pressure to implement quick fixes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Management Priorities. The maintenance team weighs the desires of the customer's management against the system's needs. Management priorities often override technical ones; managers sometimes view maintaining and enhancing as more important than building new applications. ... the rush to get a product to market may encourage us, as either developers or maintainers, to implement a quick, inelegant, poorly tested change, rather than take the time to follow good software engineering practice. The result is a patched product that is difficult to understand and repair later.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, maintainers stand to gain from participating in such studies because research aims to improve maintenance activities by better predicting fault sources, measuring maintainability, and developing tools to assist maintenance, which could make their work easier and more effective in the future.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Maintenance is a ripe area of research. Many of our maintenance activities could be made easier or more effective if we were better at predicting the likely sources of faults. Researchers are looking for better ways to measure maintainability based on product information; they are developing new models to show us the interconnections among products, processes, and resources. Similarly, the models will help us know how much effort is needed to maintain a system and when it is appropriate to retire a legacy system or rejuvenate it. Work continues on building tools to assist us in the maintenance process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, participating in such studies may help maintainers gain recognition for their skilled work, which involves not only coding but also working with users, anticipating change, and problem-solving, thereby potentially improving morale and the perceived status of maintenance roles.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Maintainers are skilled not only in writing code but also in working with users, in anticipating change, and in sleuthing. Great skill and perseverance are required to track a problem to its source, to understand the inner workings of a large system, and to modify that system's structure, code, and documentation.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A major reason for low morale is the second-class status often accorded the maintenance team.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

